    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Describe the bug\n\nenums with negative become incorrect in python. See the examples below:\n\n### Code to reproduce the behaviour:\n\n`t.py`:\n```cython\ncpdef enum ObjectTrackingEvent:\n    OBJECT_CREATED = -1\n    OBJECT_DESTROYED = -2\n```\nwith `setup.py`:\n```py\nfrom setuptools import setup\nfrom Cython.Build import cythonize\n\nsetup(\n    ext_modules = cythonize(\"t.pyx\")\n)\n```\nthen in python\n```\n❯ python\nPython 3.15.0b1 (main, May 10 2026, 19:21:12) [Clang 22.1.3 ] on darwin\nType \"help\", \"copyright\", \"credits\" or \"license\" for more information.\n>>> import t\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_CREATED\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_CREATED: 0>\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_DESTROYED\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_CREATED: 0>\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_DESTROYED.value\n0\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_CREATED.value\n0\n```\n\nIt's more strange if I combine negative and positive numbers like so\n```cython\ncpdef enum ObjectTrackingEvent:\n    TEST1 = 1\n    TEST2 = 2\n    OBJECT_CREATED = -1\n    OBJECT_DESTROYED = -2\n    OBJECT_SURVIVED = -999\n```\nThen this gets me\n```\n❯ python\nPython 3.15.0b1 (main, May 10 2026, 19:21:12) [Clang 22.1.3 ] on darwin\nType \"help\", \"copyright\", \"credits\" or \"license\" for more information.\n>>> import t\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.TEST1\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.TEST1: 1>\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.TEST2\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.TEST2: 2>\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_CREATED\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_CREATED: 3>\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_SURVIVED\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.TEST1: 1>\n>>> t.ObjectTrackingEvent.OBJECT_DESTROYED\n<ObjectTrackingEvent.TEST2: 2>\n```\n\n\n### Expected behaviour\n\n_No response_\n\n### OS\n\nmacOS\n\n### Python version\n\n3.15.0b1\n\n### Cython version\n\n3.3.0a0\n\n### Additional context\n\n_No response_",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks.\n\nWe don't currently seem to have any tests for negative enum values so we're definitely missing those.\n\nI've done a quick check on Python 3.13 and 3.14 and it seems to work for me. So I think this is new in Py3.15. Probably https://github.com/python/cpython/pull/132273\n\nWe currently use `enum.IntFlag` to define enums (or the basis that C enums are often used in a flag-like context). It sounds like that doesn't work with negative numbers any more. One option would be to use `IntEnum` instead for anything containing negative numbers. That'd have to be decided at runtime in some cases. I'm sure it'll break something though.",
